	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Retail price wars threaten long-term sustainable pricing for bananas</h1>

			
			<h4>
												26 September 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>Retail prices for bananas in UK supermarkets have once again been subject to substantial price reductions to between £0.67 and £0.74 per kilo. These price cuts are driven by the strategies adopted by supermarkets to position themselves in the context of the economic downturn. Alistair Smith of Banana Link has voiced concerns over the practice of discounting banana prices adopted by major multiple retailers, a practice which he believes serves to ‘devalue bananas in consumers minds’, thereby bringing ‘volatility to the market’. There are also concerns over the longer-term impact of these practices on prices paid to banana growers. While ‘retailers guarantee minimum prices to suppliers of fair-trade bananas’, which as a consequence ‘remain protected from the effects of discounting, ... it is a different matter in the conventional banana supply chain.’ Here, while losses were not immediately being passed on to growers, prices are being put under greater pressure when supply contracts come up for renegotiation. This results in value being squeezed out of the supply chain. In addition, according to Alistair Smith, ‘ongoing price wars in the conventional banana sector are preventing any further growth in the fair-trade market’. Smith maintains that ‘some retailers would have made the conversion to 100% fair-trade bananas if the subsequent price differentials between conventional and fair-trade weren’t so great.’ He argues that retailers committed to fair trade should abandon such price wars and instead give the signal that ‘a low price is not a fair price.’</p><p>This call for a change in attitude by the major ‘ethical’ supermarkets is supported both by small retailers and EU banana producers. Indeed, the banana growers’ union for Guadeloupe and Martinique (UGPBAN) has recently decided to stop supplying bananas to the French multiple retailer Intermarché (which takes around 10% of bananas produced on French territory), as a result of the retailer’s policy of discounting banana prices. UGPBAN representatives have argued that the corporate strategy of Intermarché is inconsistent with producers’ efforts to promote sustainable pricing for bananas that reflects the underlying reality of the cost structure faced. This action has been taken despite an acknowledgement from UGPBAN that the prices paid to producers have not so far been affected by the discounting practices pursued by Intermarché.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Bananalink, ‘UK banana prices hit the news again’, 2 September 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.bananalink.org.uk/content/view/505/166/lang,en/" target="_self">http://www.bananalink.org.uk/content/view/505/166/lang,en/</a></p><p>Bananalink, ‘French Caribbean banana producers protest against low prices’, 7 September 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://www.bananalink.org.uk/content/view/506/166/lang,en/" target="_self">http://www.bananalink.org.uk/content/view/506/166/lang,en/</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>The renewed outbreak of banana price wars in the UK and the principled stand adopted by UGPBAN suggest that issues related to the functioning of the banana supply chain are likely to take on increasing significance in the coming period. While there is an annual fluctuation reflecting seasonal over-supply, it is now assuming a structural nature and should be viewed in the context of the liberalisation under the December 2009 EU settlement of the WTO banana dispute. In this context, close consideration should be given to whether EU policy proposals currently under consideration, following a review of the functioning of the EU dairy supply chain, could usefully be extended to strengthening the functioning of the ACP-EU banana supply chain.</p><p>Similarly, Caribbean ACP banana farmers may wish to consider developing closer collaboration with farmers in the French overseas territories in pursuit of joint strategies to engage with European multiple retailers on the issue of sustainable pricing for bananas, and the need to promote differentiated schemes for bananas, such as fair trade.</p>
		</div>
		
